  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Defining the Vision**\n\nOkay, I\'m starting to get a grip on this \"retro-mod file tree web hosting system.\" I\'m picturing a nostalgic, user-friendly interface as the core. The focus is on document and occasional media file hosting within a defined \"portal.\" It seems like the goal is not to reinvent the file hosting wheel, just to present it in a unique and engaging way. I\'m moving toward an aesthetic style.\n\n\n**Refining the Aesthetic**\n\nI\'m now honing the visual direction. The \"retro-mod\" concept leans toward a sleek, high-contrast brutalist design with nostalgic cues. I\'m focusing on sharp borders, monospace fonts, and a potential dark mode that evokes both retro-futuristic and \"Win95-chic\" aesthetics. This should allow a familiar, yet modern and usable interface.\n\n\n**Structuring the Core**\n\nI\'m solidifying the UI structure. It\'ll be a single-page app with a consistent portal view. A top bar acts as a classic status bar, and a sidebar for the file tree navigation. The main content area will feature a grid or list view of files and previews. I\'m focusing on a mocked file system (JSON) to simulate navigation. This ensures a clean retro look.\n\n\n**Defining the Stack**\n\nI\'ve decided on the technical underpinnings. I\'ll use React and Tailwind for the front end, ensuring a modern build. Lucide-React will handle icons, and Framer Motion will provide subtle animations. For the fonts, I\'m thinking JetBrains Mono for a retro terminal feel paired with Inter for readability. I am ready to begin building.\n\n\n\n**Visualizing the Palette**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the color scheme. I\'m exploring a classic Macintosh/Win95-inspired brutalist aesthetic. I\'m thinking of a light beige or Windows-like gray background with sharp black borders, maybe a blue title bar, or a dark mode alternative. I\'m also considering a sleek, dark terminal/synthwave vibe, or simply a brutalist retro look with white and black. I\'m leaning toward a classic gray GUI with modern styling.\n\n\n**Adjusting the Approach**\n\nNow I\'m clarifying the visual approach, and realizing it needs refinement. The \"retro-mod\" theme shouldn\'t be too literal with inset borders. Instead, sharp outlines, bold colors, and pixel fonts for headers will provide the right feel.\n\n\\n\\n\n\nI\'m now starting to refine my approach to mocking the file data structure in `src/data.ts`. I\'m developing a TypeScript interface for the `FileNode` structure. I am also planning the app structure, including `currentPath` and `selectedFile` state within `src/App.tsx`. I am planning to break up the `App.tsx` into smaller helper components to keep things concise.\n\n\n**Outlining Implementation**\n\nI\'m now outlining the implementation plan. I\'ll start with the file structure: `src/types.ts`, `src/data.ts`, `src/components/FileTree.tsx`, `src/components/FileExplorer.tsx`, and `src/App.tsx`. Next, I\'ll update `metadata.json`, incorporate the retro font in `index.css`, and create the `FileTree` and `FileExplorer` components. Finally, I\'ll write the main `App.tsx` and lint/compile.\n\n\n**Constructing Initial Files**\n\nI\'m now drafting the initial code, mainly focusing on file creation and basic setup. My `package.json` confirms dependencies; no new ones are needed. I\'ve updated `metadata.json` with a project title and description. I\'m working on `src/index.css` to load the desired retro font and set the initial theme. I\'ve built the initial `types.ts`, `data.ts`, and a full overhaul of `App.tsx`. I am now designing the component structure and working on a recursive component (`TreeViewNode`) for file tree navigation; I\'m planning click-based navigation, not drag-and-drop. I\'m building `src/data.ts` to include documents and a few media files to match the retro vibe.\n\n\n**Defining the Palette**\n\nI am now focusing on the color scheme and overall aesthetic using the Neo-brutalist (retro-mod) approach. I\'ve chosen bg-teal-700 for the desktop, with window backgrounds as bg-gray-200 bordered by black. The title bars will be bg-blue-800 with white text, and buttons will use bg-gray-300 with black borders and shadows. This provides a nostalgic Windows 95 feel while using modern web features. I\'m also planning to use tool calls such as `edit_file` for `metadata.json` and `src/index.css` and `create_file` for `src/types.ts`, `src/data.ts`, `src/components/DesktopWindow.tsx`, `src/components/FolderTree.tsx` and `src/components/FileGrid.tsx`, as well as editing `src/App.tsx`.\n\n\n**Tracing the Imports**\n\nI\'m now tracing the component imports. Specifically, I\'m verifying the necessary imports for `App.tsx` from `src/types.ts` and `src/data.ts` to ensure everything is connected. I am making sure the type definitions and mock data are correctly used. I am working to ensure that the necessary font imports, such as JetBrains Mono and Inter, are properly loaded in the global `index.css`.\n\n\n**Implementing the Layout**\n\nI am now focusing on the main layout component (`src/App.tsx`). I\'m establishing the `currentPath` and `selectedFile` states, implementing state-driven navigation, and planning for a `currentFolder` computation. I\'ve designed the basic `DesktopWindow` structure and I\'m using icons for a retro interface.\n\n\n**Refining the Window**\n\nI\'m now refining the DesktopWindow component with black shadow effects. I\'m focusing on window chrome: title bar, minimize/maximize buttons, and content area structure. I\'m aiming for a classic Windows 95 feel with the teal desktop, gray window backgrounds, blue title bars, and black borders. I\'m writing styles in Tailwind classes, and I\'m currently focused on button styling.\n\n\n**Designing the Windows**\n\nI\'m now detailing window chrome. The title bar styling is finalized, and minimize/maximize buttons are fully functional. I\'ve got the overall DesktopWindow looking good and a toolbar implemented. It\'s using Tailwind for a Windows 95 aesthetic, and I\'m updating `src/data.ts`.\n\n\n**Updating the Data**\n\nI\'m now populating the mock data within `src/data.ts`. I\'m using a sample data structure with nested folders and various file types (documents, images, and audio). I am also working on adding content for the documents, and URLs to sample images. I\'m adding `updatedAt` and file size information.\n\n\n**Finalizing the File Viewer**\n\nI\'m now implementing the `FileViewerModal` to handle file previews. I\'m focusing on rendering different content types within the modal. I\'m adding a `<pre>` tag for documents, and displaying images via the `<img>` tag. For audio files, I\'m mocking a \"Playing Audio...\" visual. The modal component now accepts `selectedFile` and an `onClose` callback to maintain proper state. This component will be rendered as a secondary `DesktopWindow` rendered on top.\n\n\n**Confirming File Handling**\n\nI\'m now focusing on file operations, specifically avoiding direct content replacement via `edit_file`. I will use `create_file` with `Overwrite: true` for complete replacements. I am confident I can correctly use `edit_file` for partial changes by utilizing `TargetContent`. I am focusing on using the correct files.\n\nI am re-verifying the file names I am creating or editing. I am adding a new component.\n\n\n**Confirming File Handling**\n\nI\'m now switching gears to robust file management. I\'ve decided to use `create_file` with `Overwrite: true` for full content replacement in `metadata.json`, `src/index.css`, and `src/App.tsx`. I am aiming for efficiency; this ensures no partial updates and avoids target errors. This approach helps to simplify my workflow for these smaller files, while still supporting edits of larger files if necessary. I\'ve re-confirmed this is acceptable, and now I\'m making sure `src/data.ts` and `src/types.ts` are robust.\n\n\n**Defining the UI State**\n\nI\'m now integrating file management and window rendering. I\'ve defined `FileSystemNode` and related types, and now I\'m designing `src/App.tsx`. I\'ve set up `pathIDs` and `selectedFile` states for state-driven navigation, and I\'m planning a small helper function to resolve `currentFolder` from `pathIDs` and the root file structure in `src/data.ts`. I have `DesktopWindow` and `FileViewerModal` available as components. I\'m focusing on traversing up the file tree now.\n\n\n**Refining Navigation Logic**\n\nI\'m now refining the file tree navigation logic within `App.tsx`. I\'ve implemented the `resolvePath` helper to traverse the mock file system, using `pathIDs` for state-driven navigation. I\'m focusing on ensuring accurate `currentFolder` computation and seamless updates within `App.tsx`. I\'ve started building the component tree using `FileSystemNode` from the type definitions.\n\n\n**Expanding the Structure**\n\nI am now expanding the project structure. I\'m extracting the file tree into a dedicated `SidebarTree` component within `src/components`. I\'m using `create_file` to generate each of the following files: `metadata.json`, `src/index.css`, `src/types.ts`, `src/data.ts`, `src/components/DesktopWindow.tsx`, `src/components/FileViewerModal.tsx`, `src/components/SidebarTree.tsx`, and `src/App.tsx`. I am aiming for a Windows 95 visual theme with a teal background and blue selection highlights. I\'ll use a single click to open files or folders.\n\n\n**Expanding the Structure**\n\nI\'m now focusing on implementing the file system tree. I\'m importing data into a dedicated `SidebarTree` component. The system design calls for a single click to open files or folders. I\'m reviewing `FileSystemNode` and associated type definitions.\n\n\n**Implementing the Tree**\n\nI\'m now implementing the `SidebarTree` component and refining how to parse data. I\'m focusing on rendering a hierarchical file tree from mock data. I am using `FileSystemNode` and associated type definitions to render the tree. I\'ve successfully imported `data.ts` and am planning the `TreeViewNode` component as well.\n\n\n**Building the TreeView**\n\nI\'m now building out the `TreeViewNode` component as a key part of the sidebar. I\'m focusing on handling folder expansion and determining the visual state for each node. I\'m using `lucide-react` for icons and developing the `handleClick` logic for navigation. I am ensuring that I have the correct pathing for each node to build a robust component.\n\n\n**Finalizing the Tree**\n\nI\'m now integrating all logic for `TreeViewNode` and `SidebarTree`, including handling folder expansion, visual state, `handleClick` events, and path management. The tree is nearly functional, including styling and click navigation. I\'m reviewing the pathing.\n\n\n**Refining the UI**\n\nI\'m now integrating the `SidebarTree` and `DesktopWindow`. I\'m using `pathIDs` and `currentPath` states to drive navigation, and working to implement the menu bar. I\'m focusing on window chrome.\n\n\n**Integrating the Menu**\n\nI\'m now integrating the UI components, focusing on the menu and breadcrumb for improved navigation. I\'m building a toolbar with an \"Up\" button for directory navigation and a breadcrumb display. I\'m focusing on ensuring click-based state changes to update `currentPath` and maintain the path hierarchy within the UI.\n\nI\'m focusing on UI integration now; I\'m building a toolbar and refining path navigation.\n\n\n**Finalizing the File Explorer**\n\nI\'m now integrating the `SidebarTree` and focusing on file explorer functionality within the `DesktopWindow`. I\'m using path and state to render the `DesktopWindow` properly. I\'m focusing on the `FileViewerModal`.\n\nI am aiming to finalize the design.\n\n\n**Finalizing the Display**\n\nI\'m now integrating the `FileGrid` component within the `FileExplorer`. I\'m using state management to render files correctly, and I\'ve focused on displaying the file grid, including its empty state. I\'ve designed the UI to show the number of objects and storage quota. I\'m ensuring everything renders properly within the `DesktopWindow`.\n\n\n**Defining the Tailwind Colors**\n\nI\'m now implementing utility classes in Tailwind for inset and outset borders to achieve a classic Windows 95 look. I\'ve defined mappings for these border styles and implemented them in a modern brutalist context, keeping the retro aesthetic. I\'m focusing on sharp black borders and drop shadows for the primary window to exaggerate the \"retro-mod\" theme.\n\n\n**Refining Animations**\n\nI\'m now refining the animations and integration for the modal in the `FileViewerModal` component. I\'m focusing on ensuring the appearance and disappearance transitions are smooth, and I\'m updating the component in the root `App.tsx` module.\n\n\n**Finalizing the File Content**\n\nI\'m now integrating the `FileGrid` component within the `FileExplorer` to enhance file content. I\'m leveraging Tailwind utility classes to render the files and their content. For example, for documents, I am using the `<pre>` tag to render the code. I am also properly displaying images using the `<img>` tag and I\'m mocking an audio visualization for audio files.\n\n\n**Updating the Components**\n\nI\'m now integrating the modal content and desktop window events. I\'m focusing on ensuring proper closing and refactoring `FileViewerModal` for clarity. I\'ve added an `onClose` prop to the `DesktopWindow` to handle modal closure. I have now refined state management.\n\n\n**Polishing the Style**\n\nI\'m now refining the window chrome, specifically the title bars. I\'m focusing on the visual styling. The goal is a clean, classic Windows 95 feel. I\'m leveraging Tailwind classes for black borders, gray window backgrounds, and blue title bars. I am ensuring that the windows feel authentic.\n\n\n**Refining the Window**\n\nI\'m now refining the window chrome, specifically the title bars. I\'m focusing on the visual styling. The goal is a clean, classic Windows 95 feel. I\'ve switched the buttons to text-based versions to enhance authenticity, and I\'m leveraging Tailwind classes for black borders, gray window backgrounds, and blue title bars. I\'m ensuring that the windows feel authentic. I am using `create_file` now.\n\n\n**Finalizing File Integrations**\n\nI\'m now integrating the finalized components and ensuring that all parts work together seamlessly. I\'m focusing on ensuring all icons are available, from `Folder` to `HardDrive`. I\'m working with the desktop window and ensuring `motion` is in place.\n\n\\n\\n\n\nI\'ve completed integrating icons within `App.tsx` and all necessary `lucide-react` imports. I am focusing on smooth initial state within the root component now.\n\n\n**Connecting the Elements**\n\nI\'m now focusing on connecting various components and implementing data. I\'ve integrated imports in `App.tsx` and am refining smooth initial state. I am ensuring that the correct root and folder structure are present, which includes a `FileViewerModal`.\n\n\n**Refining the State**\n\nI\'m now refining the state management within `App.tsx`, focusing on path and selected file interactions. I\'ve integrated `handleNavigateUp` for directory navigation and the `handleFileAction` to control file and folder selections. I\'m focusing on UI consistency, ensuring that the selected file is correctly updated and the file tree reflects the current path.\n\n\n**Revising Double-Click Behavior**\n\nI\'m now revising the interaction model for file selection. Single clicks will highlight files, and double-clicks will execute (open folders or display files). This aligns with the classic Windows 95 behavior I\'m trying to evoke, and it feels more natural on a desktop.\n\n\n**Refining Interactions**\n\nI\'m now optimizing user interactions. Single clicks now highlight files, while double-clicks trigger actions like folder opening and file display, just as I intended. I have also added `useEffect` to reset the highlighted file when the path changes. I\'ve also incorporated necessary imports in `SidebarTree`. I\'m verifying the file structure now, including the `children` prop within `DesktopWindow`.\n\n\n"
