  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Defining the System\'s Name**\n\nI\'m focusing on the user\'s question about naming our retro-mod file hosting system. I\'ve broken it down: the request is a simple naming query, prompted by the system\'s retro design. The context is clear: a retro-styled file host. My next step will be generating potential names that capture this unique blend.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "A system designed like this typically falls into a few niche design and architectural categories, depending on what aspect you emphasize:\n\n*   **BBS (Bulletin Board System) / Web 1.0 Portal:** Functionally, it mimics the early days of the internet and dial-up networks where users navigated strict directory trees to access archived documents and media files. \n*   **Retro-Futurism / Cyberdeck UI:** Aesthetically, it heavily leans into \"retro-futurism\" or \"hacker-chic.\" It simulates terminal interfaces, mainframe consoles, or fictional operating systems (often seen in 80s/90s sci-fi movies) while combining them with modern, fast web capabilities underneath.\n*   **Lo-Fi or Brutalist UI:** Structurally, it ignores modern UI trends (like soft drop-shadows, rounded corners, and floating elements) in favor of harsh contrasts, exposed borders, dense monospace typography, and rigid grid layouts. \n*   **Skeuomorphic Desktop/TUI Environment:** It borrows concepts from early windowed operating systems (like Windows 95 or early Mac OS) and Text User Interfaces (TUIs, like MS-DOS or Unix shells), framing web content inside simulated windows, title bars, and directories.\n\nIn modern web design, developers often refer to this specific blend simply as **\"Retro-Mod\"**, **\"Terminal-style\"**, or a **\"Retro Desktop UI\"**\342\200\224offering the deep nostalgia of legacy computing with the seamless performance of a modern web application!"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 2
      nanos: 680866754
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
