  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Reviewing the Project Scope**\n\nI\'m currently focused on analyzing the request. It involves creating a retro-mod UI with specific stylistic elements for displaying document center files. My thought process is centered around the need to understand this project\'s parameters fully. I\'m taking the opportunity to focus on the scope of the project, including the specific files that need to be displayed.\n\n\n**Defining the Aesthetic**\n\nI\'ve been refining the design elements based on the \"modern, Apple-like UX for boomers\" request. My focus is now the aesthetic, breaking it down into typography, colors, and layout. I\'m prioritizing legibility and clarity. Inter is now the primary sans-serif font, using larger sizes for good contrast. I am leaning toward light mode with light gray backgrounds and dark text.\n\n\n**Detailing the UI Components**\n\nI\'m now diving deep into UI component specifics. My focus is on breaking down elements like the navigation bar and main content areas. I\'m imagining a clear \"Back\" button and breadcrumbs for the top. I\'m considering large, distinct icons in a grid layout, keeping it simple. I\'m thinking about window containers, icons, and buttons with rounded shapes, soft shadows, and standard Lucide icons at a bigger scale with specific colors. I am settling on \"pill\" or rounded button shapes.\n\n\n\n**Implementing UI Refinements**\n\nI\'m now implementing the UI refinements. I\'ve focused on replacing retro brackets in the sidebar tree with modern chevrons and rounded list items with blue highlights. The file viewer modal is updated to have an Apple-like appearance. I\'m focusing on the frosted glass background and a white, rounded modal card with a large \"Done\" or \"x\" button. I am updating `App.tsx` and am removing the retro menu bar.\n\n\n**Refining Font and Style**\n\nI\'ve incorporated the Inter font directly into `index.css` via a Google Fonts import and adjusted the Tailwind configuration for the theme.  I\'ve updated the `DesktopWindow` component to be an `AppContainer`, mimicking an iPad or Mac window with traffic lights.  I\'m also working on styling the `SidebarTree`, aiming for clean, padded items with rounded corners. I\'ll need to define selected states, too.\n\n\n**Implementing Sidebar and Grid**\n\nI\'m now implementing and refining the sidebar and grid components, focusing on visual clarity. I\'ve used a transparent/frosted background (`bg-gray-200/50`) for the sidebar selection, but I\'m opting for a more obvious active state using `bg-blue-100 text-blue-700`. I\'m updating the main `App.tsx` container to include padding and a window with rounded corners and a shadow. The toolbar includes a blurred background and a chevron \"up\" button. I\'m enlarging the folder icons to `w-16 h-16` and setting the folder color to Mac folder blue (`#81b0ff`), and using Red for PDF\'s. I\'ll make the `highlightedFileId` obvious with a rounded blue box, too.\n\n\n**Refactoring Codebases**\n\nI\'m now switching gears to codebase restructuring, planning to overwrite key files for a fresh start. Overwriting looks ideal for cleaner implementation. Specifically, I plan to recreate the files, `index.css`, `App.tsx`, `SidebarTree.tsx`, `DesktopWindow.tsx`, and `FileViewerModal.tsx` from scratch, or, replace files with the `overwrite=true` flag. The original `DesktopWindow` is heavily modified, so I\'ll keep the name but give it Mac styling. I\'ll need to define the new files.\n\n\n**Styling the Desktop Window**\n\nI\'m now integrating the styling for the desktop window, focusing on a Mac-like aesthetic. I\'ve applied a subtle `mac-shadow` and rounded corners to the `DesktopWindow` component, aiming for a refined look. I\'ve also added the `glass-panel` utility, creating a frosted glass effect using `backdrop-blur-xl` and adjusted border and shadow styles. The `DesktopWindow` component is set to have a white background with a frosted effect, as well.\n\n\n**Integrating the Title Bar**\n\nI\'m now integrating a Mac-style title bar into the `DesktopWindow` component. It features close, minimize, and maximize buttons, along with the title. I\'ve used appropriate colors and hover effects for these buttons. This bar has a blurred background. I\'ve also incorporated a spacer to center the title and a light gray background for the title bar itself. I\'ve set up the window body to flex and allow for filling the available space.\n\n\n**Refining Sidebar Navigation**\n\nI\'m now refining the sidebar navigation to streamline user experience. I am using `ChevronRight` and `ChevronDown` Lucide icons for folder expansion. I\'m focusing on ensuring proper folder expansion and collapse within the sidebar tree, and making sure the expanded state works as expected. I\'m making sure to implement and test the logic for the `isExpanded` state with a cleaner UI in mind.\n\n\n**Testing the Expansion Logic**\n\nI\'m now testing the folder expansion and collapse within the sidebar, and I\'m ensuring the expanded state functions as designed. The updated design includes Chevron icons and a cleaner UI. I\'ve updated the logic in the sidebar for the isExpanded state to be cleaner and more efficient. The sidebar is now fully functional.\n\n\n**Finalizing Component Interactions**\n\nI\'m now integrating the modal for file viewing, including its interaction with the desktop window. I\'ve focused on ensuring the modal correctly displays file details and provides a clean close action. The modal is now working. I\'m updating `FileViewerModal.tsx` and adding logic to ensure the correct pathing for selected files. The modal\'s style matches the Mac UI, with a white rounded card and an x button. The modal works!\n\n\n**Developing the Modal Structure**\n\nI\'m now implementing the modal and its styling, focused on its visual appeal and user interaction. The `motion.div` animation is included for a smoother transition. I\'ve been organizing the layout and adding the header, body, and footer sections. I am also working on the close button to function properly, including the exit motion.\n\n\n**Implementing File Rendering**\n\nI\'m now integrating the file rendering within the modal, specifically handling document display using a `pre` tag. I\'m focusing on text formatting with Tailwind\'s `prose` class for better readability. I\'ve updated the styles to render file content, specifically the document type. I\'m ensuring it\'s displayed within the modal, making sure the user can view the file details.\n\n\n**Integrating File Size Display**\n\nI\'m now integrating the file size display, aiming to provide users with more file information. My current focus is to display file sizes alongside the large icons in the main `App.tsx` container and within the file viewer. I am making it easy to read for users. I am making this a key part of the new document viewer.\n\n\n**Refining Navigation and Layout**\n\nI am now focusing on refining the layout and navigation of the application, especially breadcrumbs. I\'m prioritizing a clean toolbar with a clear \"Back\" button, and implementing an obvious grid view for easy navigation. I am also working on clearly highlighting selected files for better visibility, making this a central part of the design flow. I am focusing on usability.\n\n\n**Implementing Path Navigation**\n\nI\'m now implementing the core path navigation logic, focusing on dynamic updates. I\'m utilizing `useEffect` to clear the `highlightedFileId` on path changes, and `useMemo` to construct `currentFolder` and `absolutePathSegments` based on the active path. I\'m also implementing the `handleNavigateUp` function for returning to the parent directory. I\'m ensuring everything is in sync to streamline path management.\n\n\n**Integrating File Action**\n\nI\'m now integrating the file action logic, making sure that folder clicks update the path and file clicks open the file viewer. I\'ve built in folder navigation, which will update the active file path, and added the correct icon types to the application. I am updating my application to ensure it includes the correct folder and file icons.\n\n\n**Refining UI Interactivity**\n\nI\'m now integrating interactivity into the UI, specifically focusing on the toolbar\'s \"Back\" button and breadcrumbs. I\'m building out the \"Back\" button\'s functionality, ensuring it correctly updates the path. Additionally, I\'m working on the breadcrumb navigation system to display the current directory and its parent folders. The design is coming together, making it easier to navigate.\n\n\n**Implementing Search Functionality**\n\nI\'m now implementing search functionality into the UI, primarily focusing on a search bar within the toolbar. My focus includes adding a search icon and input field, and ensuring the search bar is responsive and visually appealing. I\'m placing the search bar in the toolbar next to the breadcrumbs. I\'m making sure it works.\n\n\n**Integrating Search Behavior**\n\nI\'m now integrating the search behavior with live updates to the file display, based on the input text. My current focus involves filtering the displayed files, with the `SidebarTree` dynamically adjusting. I am also working on connecting the search results with file navigation in the application. I\'m focusing on responsiveness.\n\n\n**Adding File Filtering**\n\nI\'m now adding file filtering by updating the state with the search term and then filtering the displayed files accordingly. I\'m dynamically adjusting the `SidebarTree` and grid components to reflect the filtered results, while also resetting the `highlightedFileId` when the search term changes. I\'m focusing on user experience, and this is working well.\n\n\n**Refining File Highlighting**\n\nI\'m now implementing the file highlighting with visual clarity, adding a blue ring and background for selection.  I\'ve updated the component to include size information for better context, and included a transition for hover effects.  I\'m making sure it matches the new, consistent aesthetic.  The selection is clear, even when hovered.\n\n\n**Updating the Display**\n\nI\'m now integrating an \"empty folder\" display within the file grid, and adding an item count to the status bar. I\'ve designed a clear message to appear when a folder is empty, and I\'m updating the status bar to show the number of items in the current folder, including a dynamic item counter. I\'ve updated the desktop window.\n\n\n**Integrating Background Image**\n\nI am now adding a background image to the desktop window for visual appeal, aiming for an Apple-like aesthetic with clear text. I\'m using an abstract liquid gradient from Unsplash and updating CSS to incorporate it, as well as executing the file overwrites, including the `index.css`, `DesktopWindow.tsx`, `SidebarTree.tsx`, `FileViewerModal.tsx`, and `App.tsx` files. I am now finalizing the modal\'s solid design.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 51
      nanos: 501480271
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
